</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Oncologic patients are treated with a combination of chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and surgery. Advances in therapeutic options have greatly improved the survival of patients with cancer. Examples of these advances are newer chemotherapeutic agents that target the cell receptors and advanced radiation therapy delivery systems. It is imperative that radiologists be aware of the variety of imaging findings seen after therapy in patients with cancer. Complications may occur with classic cytotoxic therapies (eg, 5-fluorouracil), usually at higher or prolonged doses or when administered to radiosensitive areas. Newer targeted systemic agents, such as bevacizumab and imatinib, have associated characteristic toxicities because their effects on cells do not depend on dose. Radiation may induce early and late effects in local normal tissues that may be seen at imaging. Imaging findings after chemotherapy include fatty liver, pseudocirrhosis, hepatic veno-occlusive disease, and splenic rupture. Complications of radiation therapy include large and small bowel strictures and radiation-induced hepatitis and tumors. Awareness of the various therapeutic options and knowledge of the spectrum of posttherapeutic complications allows radiologists to provide a comprehensive report that may impact patient management.</div><div role="paragraph">©RSNA, 2014</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.344140082">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.344140082">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig1a.jpeg" height="710" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> Unusual fat deposition in a 72-year-old woman with pancreatic head adenocarcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image after 3 months of gemcitabine therapy shows multiple low-attenuation lesions in segment IV (arrows). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial in-phase <b>(b)</b> and out-of-phase <b>(c)</b> MR images show that the lesions (arrows) demonstrate signal dropout on the out-of-phase image, a finding consistent with fat infiltration. Knowledge of the atypical appearance of fat infiltration in the liver from chemotherapeutic changes is important to avoid misinterpreting these lesions as metastases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig1b.jpeg" height="719" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> Unusual fat deposition in a 72-year-old woman with pancreatic head adenocarcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image after 3 months of gemcitabine therapy shows multiple low-attenuation lesions in segment IV (arrows). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial in-phase <b>(b)</b> and out-of-phase <b>(c)</b> MR images show that the lesions (arrows) demonstrate signal dropout on the out-of-phase image, a finding consistent with fat infiltration. Knowledge of the atypical appearance of fat infiltration in the liver from chemotherapeutic changes is important to avoid misinterpreting these lesions as metastases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig1c.jpeg" height="719" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span> Unusual fat deposition in a 72-year-old woman with pancreatic head adenocarcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image after 3 months of gemcitabine therapy shows multiple low-attenuation lesions in segment IV (arrows). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial in-phase <b>(b)</b> and out-of-phase <b>(c)</b> MR images show that the lesions (arrows) demonstrate signal dropout on the out-of-phase image, a finding consistent with fat infiltration. Knowledge of the atypical appearance of fat infiltration in the liver from chemotherapeutic changes is important to avoid misinterpreting these lesions as metastases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig2a.jpeg" height="629" width="959" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> Hepatic capsular retraction in a 47-year-old woman with metastatic breast cancer. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image obtained before treatment shows diffuse metastatic disease in the liver. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image obtained after 3 months of capecitabine therapy shows new marked hepatic capsular retraction, a condition that mimics cirrhosis; knowledge of this complication is important to avoid misinterpreting findings.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig2b.jpeg" height="629" width="916" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> Hepatic capsular retraction in a 47-year-old woman with metastatic breast cancer. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image obtained before treatment shows diffuse metastatic disease in the liver. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image obtained after 3 months of capecitabine therapy shows new marked hepatic capsular retraction, a condition that mimics cirrhosis; knowledge of this complication is important to avoid misinterpreting findings.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig3a.jpeg" height="669" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Portal vein branch thrombosis in a 61-year-old woman with colorectal carcinoma and hepatic metastatic disease. <b>(a)</b> CT image obtained before therapy shows liver metastasis (*) and a patent right portal vein branch (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> CT image obtained after 3 months of FOLFIRI and bevacizumab therapy shows diffuse fat changes in the liver with sparing of segment VIII, a thrombus in the portal vein branch (arrowheads) supplying segment VIII, and an associated perfusion abnormality. An atypical appearance of fat infiltration in the liver raises the possibility of a focal vascular or perfusion abnormality. <b>(c)</b> CT image obtained 4 months after the start of therapy shows complete occlusion of the right portal vein (arrowhead) and a decrease in the size of the liver metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig3b.jpeg" height="658" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Portal vein branch thrombosis in a 61-year-old woman with colorectal carcinoma and hepatic metastatic disease. <b>(a)</b> CT image obtained before therapy shows liver metastasis (*) and a patent right portal vein branch (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> CT image obtained after 3 months of FOLFIRI and bevacizumab therapy shows diffuse fat changes in the liver with sparing of segment VIII, a thrombus in the portal vein branch (arrowheads) supplying segment VIII, and an associated perfusion abnormality. An atypical appearance of fat infiltration in the liver raises the possibility of a focal vascular or perfusion abnormality. <b>(c)</b> CT image obtained 4 months after the start of therapy shows complete occlusion of the right portal vein (arrowhead) and a decrease in the size of the liver metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig3c.jpeg" height="659" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span> Portal vein branch thrombosis in a 61-year-old woman with colorectal carcinoma and hepatic metastatic disease. <b>(a)</b> CT image obtained before therapy shows liver metastasis (*) and a patent right portal vein branch (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> CT image obtained after 3 months of FOLFIRI and bevacizumab therapy shows diffuse fat changes in the liver with sparing of segment VIII, a thrombus in the portal vein branch (arrowheads) supplying segment VIII, and an associated perfusion abnormality. An atypical appearance of fat infiltration in the liver raises the possibility of a focal vascular or perfusion abnormality. <b>(c)</b> CT image obtained 4 months after the start of therapy shows complete occlusion of the right portal vein (arrowhead) and a decrease in the size of the liver metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig4a.jpeg" height="723" width="910" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Sinusoidal obstruction syndrome resulting from oxaliplatin therapy in a 59-year-old woman with rectal adenocarcinoma and liver metastases. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image obtained after 4 months of capecitabine and high-dose oxaliplatin therapy shows a mottled appearance of the liver, a finding indicative of sinusoidal obstruction syndrome, and a slight increase in the size of the spleen. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image obtained 2 months later shows new marked ascites (*), continuing liver abnormality, and an increase in the size of the spleen. Paracentesis was performed to exclude malignancy in the fluid, and pathologic analysis revealed transudate. The presence of ascites and heterogeneity of the liver is a result of liver damage from oxaliplatin therapy. Knowledge of this complication may prevent mistaking this condition for metastatic disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig4b.jpeg" height="723" width="965" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Sinusoidal obstruction syndrome resulting from oxaliplatin therapy in a 59-year-old woman with rectal adenocarcinoma and liver metastases. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image obtained after 4 months of capecitabine and high-dose oxaliplatin therapy shows a mottled appearance of the liver, a finding indicative of sinusoidal obstruction syndrome, and a slight increase in the size of the spleen. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image obtained 2 months later shows new marked ascites (*), continuing liver abnormality, and an increase in the size of the spleen. Paracentesis was performed to exclude malignancy in the fluid, and pathologic analysis revealed transudate. The presence of ascites and heterogeneity of the liver is a result of liver damage from oxaliplatin therapy. Knowledge of this complication may prevent mistaking this condition for metastatic disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig5.jpeg" height="651" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span> Hepatic congestion in a 55-year-old man with renal cell carcinoma. Axial CT image obtained after 2 months of pazopanib therapy shows right pleural effusion (*) and heterogeneity of the liver parenchyma, findings consistent with congestion and that indicate congestive heart failure. Cardiologic examination and echocardiography revealed that the ejection fraction decreased from 60% to 20% after administration of chemotherapy. <i>M</i> = renal cell carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig6.jpeg" height="603" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span> Splenic rupture in a 55-year-old man with leiomyosarcoma and liver metastases who is undergoing imatinib therapy and recently began clopidogrel therapy. Axial CT image obtained 1 month after initiation of imatinib therapy shows a new fluid collection around the spleen <i>(S)</i> in the left upper quadrant, a finding that represents hemoperitoneum, with heterogeneous attenuation consistent with active bleeding. An adjacent muscular hematoma (*) is also seen. Caution should be used when administering imatinib in conjunction with clopidogrel because hemorrhage may be catastrophic.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig7a.jpeg" height="643" width="911" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Oxaliplatin-induced splenomegaly in a 56-year-old man with metastatic colorectal carcinoma who is undergoing FOLFOX and bevacizumab therapy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows hepatic metastases <i>(M)</i> and a normal splenic size. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image obtained 6 months after therapy shows a decrease in the size of the hepatic metastases but an increase in splenic size. Because of the presence of thrombocytopenia, oxaliplatin therapy was halted. Usually, thrombocytopenia regresses once therapy is stopped; however, in this case, sequestration of platelets continued, and splenic arterial embolization was performed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig7b.jpeg" height="643" width="964" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Oxaliplatin-induced splenomegaly in a 56-year-old man with metastatic colorectal carcinoma who is undergoing FOLFOX and bevacizumab therapy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows hepatic metastases <i>(M)</i> and a normal splenic size. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image obtained 6 months after therapy shows a decrease in the size of the hepatic metastases but an increase in splenic size. Because of the presence of thrombocytopenia, oxaliplatin therapy was halted. Usually, thrombocytopenia regresses once therapy is stopped; however, in this case, sequestration of platelets continued, and splenic arterial embolization was performed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig8.jpeg" height="644" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span> Spleen after Thorotrast in a 69-year-old woman with lymphoma. Initial screening CT image shows characteristic diffuse high attenuation in the spleen, a result of deposition of Thorotrast. Imaging evaluation of patients who were exposed to Thorotrast, which was used in the 1930s and 1940s, should be tailored for close follow-up because the risk for secondary malignancies, such as biliary duct cancer and leukemia, is high.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig9.jpeg" height="656" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span> Colitis in a 40-year-old woman with leiomyosarcoma who presented with abdominal pain and diarrhea 2 months after beginning docetaxel therapy. CT image shows diffuse colonic wall thickening (*) and small reactive ileocolic nodes (arrows), findings consistent with pancolitis. Cessation of chemotherapy alleviated the symptoms.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig10a.jpeg" height="666" width="937" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Delayed anastomotic leak in a 50-year-old man with rectal adenocarcinoma who underwent 6 months of preoperative FOLFIRI and bevacizumab therapy and low anterior resection in 2009. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image obtained after low anterior resection shows unremarkable postoperative changes. <b>(b)</b> Follow-up axial CT image obtained after 6 months of postoperative FOLFIRI and bevacizumab chemotherapy shows air and an extraluminal fluid collection with contrast material (arrows) adjacent to the anastomosis site. In contrast to recurrent tumor, there is no splaying of the sutures from rectal surgery. Given the long interval of 21 months from the time of surgery, this finding is highly suspicious for a delayed anastomotic leak from bevacizumab therapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig10b.jpeg" height="666" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Delayed anastomotic leak in a 50-year-old man with rectal adenocarcinoma who underwent 6 months of preoperative FOLFIRI and bevacizumab therapy and low anterior resection in 2009. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image obtained after low anterior resection shows unremarkable postoperative changes. <b>(b)</b> Follow-up axial CT image obtained after 6 months of postoperative FOLFIRI and bevacizumab chemotherapy shows air and an extraluminal fluid collection with contrast material (arrows) adjacent to the anastomosis site. In contrast to recurrent tumor, there is no splaying of the sutures from rectal surgery. Given the long interval of 21 months from the time of surgery, this finding is highly suspicious for a delayed anastomotic leak from bevacizumab therapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig11.jpeg" height="636" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span> GVHD in a 2-year-old boy with acute lymphocytic leukemia who presented with diarrhea, abdominal pain, and gastrointestinal bleeding 60 days after undergoing single-cord blood stem-cell transplantation. Axial CT image shows diffuse thickening and enhancement of the small bowel mucosa (*) and thickening of the large bowel wall (arrowheads), a manifestation that is highly suspicious for GVHD. Ascites is also present. Diffuse involvement of both the small and large bowel paired with skin lesions (or other sites of GVHD) is highly suggestive of GVHD. GVHD was also present in the eyes. Grade IV GVHD was confirmed at biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig12a.jpeg" height="704" width="986" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> Pneumatosis in a 56-year-old man with metastatic colon cancer and liver and lung metastases after undergoing 8 months of FOLFIRI and cetuximab therapy. Axial CT images obtained with soft-tissue <b>(a)</b> and lung <b>(b)</b> window settings show pneumatosis in the hepatic flexure (arrows), a finding that may be seen after administration of chemotherapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig12b.jpeg" height="704" width="889" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> Pneumatosis in a 56-year-old man with metastatic colon cancer and liver and lung metastases after undergoing 8 months of FOLFIRI and cetuximab therapy. Axial CT images obtained with soft-tissue <b>(a)</b> and lung <b>(b)</b> window settings show pneumatosis in the hepatic flexure (arrows), a finding that may be seen after administration of chemotherapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig13.jpeg" height="694" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span> Hemorrhage in a 61-year-old woman with breast cancer and progressive metastatic disease to the liver who was given one dose of bevacizumab, trastuzumab, and ixabepilone therapy and presented to the emergency room with severe abdominal pain and decreased hemoglobin level (from 10 g/dL to 6 g/dL) that same evening. Axial CT image obtained at the level of the liver shows a subcapsular fluid collection with heterogeneous attenuation (40–60 HU), a finding consistent with hemorrhage, adjacent to a hepatic metastasis that is bleeding (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig14a.jpeg" height="658" width="947" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> Old hemorrhage in a 44-year-old patient with a metastatic gastrointestinal stromal tumor, fatigue, and hypertension who is undergoing sunitinib therapy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image obtained in November shows metastases in the liver. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image obtained after 5 months of sunitinib therapy shows a new low-attenuation collection with high-attenuation content in a dependent location (arrowheads), a finding suggestive of an old hematoma, with a tail-like extension to a metastasis that has increased in size (arrow). Hemorrhage is a complication of therapy, and the increase in size and fluid collection should not be confused with progression.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig14b.jpeg" height="658" width="928" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> Old hemorrhage in a 44-year-old patient with a metastatic gastrointestinal stromal tumor, fatigue, and hypertension who is undergoing sunitinib therapy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image obtained in November shows metastases in the liver. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image obtained after 5 months of sunitinib therapy shows a new low-attenuation collection with high-attenuation content in a dependent location (arrowheads), a finding suggestive of an old hematoma, with a tail-like extension to a metastasis that has increased in size (arrow). Hemorrhage is a complication of therapy, and the increase in size and fluid collection should not be confused with progression.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig15.jpeg" height="773" width="700" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span> Fluid retention and ascites in a 47-year-old patient with a small bowel gastrointestinal stromal tumor. Axial CT image obtained after 3 months of imatinib therapy shows new pericholecystic fluid and ascites, a result of therapy, not metastatic disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig16a.jpeg" height="697" width="853" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> Focal hepatic radiation change in a 57-year-old man with carcinoma of the esophagus who underwent radiation therapy with 50.4 Gy to the esophagus and fluorouracil and docetaxel chemotherapy. <b>(a)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained 1 month after the completion of therapy shows an FDG-avid focus in the left lobe of the liver (arrow) and the known esophageal mass (*). <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows the liver lesion (arrow) to have high signal intensity, a finding consistent with edema. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image obtained during radiation treatment planning shows a high radiation dose to be delivered to the area of the liver abnormality. Knowledge of the expected findings of radiation-induced liver injuries is important to prevent misinterpreting such injuries as a liver metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig16b.jpeg" height="697" width="922" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> Focal hepatic radiation change in a 57-year-old man with carcinoma of the esophagus who underwent radiation therapy with 50.4 Gy to the esophagus and fluorouracil and docetaxel chemotherapy. <b>(a)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained 1 month after the completion of therapy shows an FDG-avid focus in the left lobe of the liver (arrow) and the known esophageal mass (*). <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows the liver lesion (arrow) to have high signal intensity, a finding consistent with edema. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image obtained during radiation treatment planning shows a high radiation dose to be delivered to the area of the liver abnormality. Knowledge of the expected findings of radiation-induced liver injuries is important to prevent misinterpreting such injuries as a liver metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig16c.jpeg" height="808" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span> Focal hepatic radiation change in a 57-year-old man with carcinoma of the esophagus who underwent radiation therapy with 50.4 Gy to the esophagus and fluorouracil and docetaxel chemotherapy. <b>(a)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained 1 month after the completion of therapy shows an FDG-avid focus in the left lobe of the liver (arrow) and the known esophageal mass (*). <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows the liver lesion (arrow) to have high signal intensity, a finding consistent with edema. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image obtained during radiation treatment planning shows a high radiation dose to be delivered to the area of the liver abnormality. Knowledge of the expected findings of radiation-induced liver injuries is important to prevent misinterpreting such injuries as a liver metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig17a.jpeg" height="667" width="680" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span> Late radiation-induced sigmoid stricture in a 61-year-old woman with endometrial cancer who presented with cramps and blood-tinged diarrhea 1 year after undergoing 50.4 Gy whole-pelvis radiation therapy, 43.5 Gy paraaortic radiation therapy, and brachytherapy. <b>(a)</b> Image from a barium enema study shows marked narrowing of the sigmoid colon (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Corresponding axial CT image shows a diffuse small bowel with sigmoid and rectal thickening, a result of radiation change. Thickening should not be mistaken for tumoral involvement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig17b.jpeg" height="668" width="895" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span> Late radiation-induced sigmoid stricture in a 61-year-old woman with endometrial cancer who presented with cramps and blood-tinged diarrhea 1 year after undergoing 50.4 Gy whole-pelvis radiation therapy, 43.5 Gy paraaortic radiation therapy, and brachytherapy. <b>(a)</b> Image from a barium enema study shows marked narrowing of the sigmoid colon (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Corresponding axial CT image shows a diffuse small bowel with sigmoid and rectal thickening, a result of radiation change. Thickening should not be mistaken for tumoral involvement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig18a.jpeg" height="704" width="889" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span> Sigmoid fistula to the sacroiliac joint and osteomyelitis in a 67-year-old woman with endometrial adenocarcinoma that was originally diagnosed in 1995. Total abdominal hysterectomy was performed at that time, with subsequent external beam radiation therapy (45 Gy) followed by six cycles of chemotherapy, which was completed in October 1996. Radioactive seeds were also implanted in the left hip. In 2009, the patient presented with abdominal pain, hip pain, limited movement, and fever. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows air in the left iliopsoas muscle (arrow), a finding suggestive of a fistula, and sclerosis and destruction of the left sacroiliac joint (arrowhead), a finding consistent with osteoradionecrosis and osteomyelitis. <b>(b)</b> Image from a barium enema study shows a long collection of extraluminal contrast material (arrows) extending from the sigmoid colon, a finding consistent with a fistula between the sigmoid colon and the left sacroiliac joint.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig18b.jpeg" height="704" width="786" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span> Sigmoid fistula to the sacroiliac joint and osteomyelitis in a 67-year-old woman with endometrial adenocarcinoma that was originally diagnosed in 1995. Total abdominal hysterectomy was performed at that time, with subsequent external beam radiation therapy (45 Gy) followed by six cycles of chemotherapy, which was completed in October 1996. Radioactive seeds were also implanted in the left hip. In 2009, the patient presented with abdominal pain, hip pain, limited movement, and fever. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows air in the left iliopsoas muscle (arrow), a finding suggestive of a fistula, and sclerosis and destruction of the left sacroiliac joint (arrowhead), a finding consistent with osteoradionecrosis and osteomyelitis. <b>(b)</b> Image from a barium enema study shows a long collection of extraluminal contrast material (arrows) extending from the sigmoid colon, a finding consistent with a fistula between the sigmoid colon and the left sacroiliac joint.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig19a.jpeg" height="659" width="937" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span> Recurrent tumor in a 66-year-old man with a history of ulcerative colitis and rectal cancer who, 3 years earlier, underwent proctocolectomy with end ileostomy and adjuvant FOLFOX and bevacizumab chemotherapy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image obtained after completion of therapy shows presacral thickening with no evidence of a mass. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image, obtained 1.5 years later because of increasing carcinoembryonic antigen levels, shows an enhancing nodule (arrow) within the area of presacral thickening. <b>(c)</b> Axial PET/CT image shows a local tumor recurrence in the pelvis (standardized uptake value, 15.1). Biopsy was performed, and recurrent disease was confirmed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig19b.jpeg" height="659" width="937" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span> Recurrent tumor in a 66-year-old man with a history of ulcerative colitis and rectal cancer who, 3 years earlier, underwent proctocolectomy with end ileostomy and adjuvant FOLFOX and bevacizumab chemotherapy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image obtained after completion of therapy shows presacral thickening with no evidence of a mass. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image, obtained 1.5 years later because of increasing carcinoembryonic antigen levels, shows an enhancing nodule (arrow) within the area of presacral thickening. <b>(c)</b> Axial PET/CT image shows a local tumor recurrence in the pelvis (standardized uptake value, 15.1). Biopsy was performed, and recurrent disease was confirmed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig19c.jpeg" height="608" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig19c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19c</span> Recurrent tumor in a 66-year-old man with a history of ulcerative colitis and rectal cancer who, 3 years earlier, underwent proctocolectomy with end ileostomy and adjuvant FOLFOX and bevacizumab chemotherapy. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image obtained after completion of therapy shows presacral thickening with no evidence of a mass. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image, obtained 1.5 years later because of increasing carcinoembryonic antigen levels, shows an enhancing nodule (arrow) within the area of presacral thickening. <b>(c)</b> Axial PET/CT image shows a local tumor recurrence in the pelvis (standardized uptake value, 15.1). Biopsy was performed, and recurrent disease was confirmed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig19c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig20.jpeg" height="607" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span> Radiation-induced hepatic angiosarcoma in a 32-year-old woman who twice underwent total abdominal radiation therapy at age 4 to treat ovarian malignant teratoma. Axial CT image shows hepatomegaly with multiple enhancing irregular masses throughout the liver. Angiosarcoma was proved at biopsy. The patient’s history of abdominal radiation, the long latency period (28 years), and the pathologic finding of sarcoma are consistent with a radiation-induced tumor. With improvements in systemic chemo- and radiation therapy, patients are now living longer, which increases the chance of developing a radiation-induced secondary tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig21a.jpeg" height="600" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span> Radiation-induced sarcoma in a 63-year-old woman with a history of dysgerminoma 51 years ago that was treated with cobalt therapy and endometrial carcinoma 31 years ago that was treated with brachytherapy. Axial CT <b>(a)</b> and coronal short inversion time inversion-recovery MR <b>(b)</b> images show a soft-tissue mass and sacral destruction (arrow in <b>b</b>). Results of biopsy revealed spindle cell sarcoma. The patient’s history of radiation, long latency period (more than 50 years), and pathologic findings indicate radiation-induced sarcoma. Typically, secondary malignancies occur 20–30 years after radiation therapy, but they may appear as early as 7 years.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.344140082/asset/images/large/rg.344140082.fig21b.jpeg" height="669" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span> Radiation-induced sarcoma in a 63-year-old woman with a history of dysgerminoma 51 years ago that was treated with cobalt therapy and endometrial carcinoma 31 years ago that was treated with brachytherapy. Axial CT <b>(a)</b> and coronal short inversion time inversion-recovery MR <b>(b)</b> images show a soft-tissue mass and sacral destruction (arrow in <b>b</b>). Results of biopsy revealed spindle cell sarcoma. The patient’s history of radiation, long latency period (more than 50 years), and pathologic findings indicate radiation-induced sarcoma. Typically, secondary malignancies occur 20–30 years after radiation therapy, but they may appear as early as 7 years.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.344140082&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Cook KM, Figg WD. Angiogenesis inhibitors: current strategies and future prospects. <em>CA Cancer J Clin</em> 2010;60(4):222–243.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.3322/caac.20075">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20554717/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Angiogenesis+inhibitors%3A+current+strategies+and+future+prospects&amp;author=KM+Cook&amp;author=WD+Figg&amp;publication_year=2010&amp;journal=CA+Cancer+J+Clin&amp;pages=222-243&amp;doi=10.3322%2Fcaac.20075&amp;